<methodology slug="ai-enhanced-design-systems">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>AI scales a mature design system by automating documentation, detecting token violations, and generating variants — but only when the system has well-defined tokens and systematic structure.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>design-systems</tag>
      <tag>design-tokens</tag>
      <tag>component-documentation</tag>
      <tag>automation</tag>
      <tag>ai-amplification</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AI-Enhanced Design Systems</title>
    <summary>AI scales a mature design system by automating component documentation, detecting hardcoded token violations, and generating variant permutations — but only when the system already has well-defined tokens, systematic component structure, and clear naming conventions. AI amplifies the existing foundation; it does not create one.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Scaling design systems manually requires significant effort per component (props documentation, usage examples, accessibility notes, do/don't guidance). AI documentation generation and token audit scripts reduce this to minutes per component, while Chromatic visual regression catches AI-generated variant drift before merge.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>A mature design system exists with defined tokens and component structure; you want AI to scale it</item>
        <item>Automating component documentation generation from existing component code and stories</item>
        <item>Detecting token usage inconsistencies across a large codebase where manual audit is impractical</item>
        <item>Generating component variant permutations (size, state, density) from a seed component</item>
        <item>Producing design token suggestions when the system is evolving (new brand palette, dark mode)</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>The design system has no defined tokens, naming conventions, or systematic component structure — AI amplifies deficiencies</item>
        <item>You need AI to create the foundational design system from scratch — requires human-led design first</item>
        <item>The component library has fewer than 10 components — manual documentation is faster</item>
        <item>The primary problem is design-engineering alignment, not documentation scale — that is a process problem</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Amplification Principle">
      <rule>
        <statement>AI will amplify the existing design system foundation — it will not create one from nothing. Do not use AI to build foundational design system structure.</statement>
        <rationale>AI-generated component variants inherit semantic errors from the seed component. A broken foundation produces broken variants at scale. Human-led system design must precede AI automation.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Required Prerequisites">
      <list>
        <item>Well-defined design tokens (color, spacing, typography, shadow)</item>
        <item>Systematic component structure with clear naming conventions</item>
        <item>Documented token-to-component relationships</item>
        <item>Style Dictionary or equivalent as single source of truth</item>
        <item>At least 10 components before AI documentation automation pays off</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI Capabilities Once Prerequisites Met">
      <list>
        <item>Component documentation: generate props table, usage examples, accessibility notes, do/don't guidance</item>
        <item>Token audit: detect hardcoded values (hex colors, px spacing) that should be token references</item>
        <item>Variant generation: scale out size, state, density variants from seed component</item>
        <item>Inconsistency detection: find components not following naming or token conventions</item>
        <item>Dark mode adaptation: suggest token mappings for light/dark theme pairs</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Tool Landscape">
      <list>
        <item>Figma REST API — read token/component data programmatically</item>
        <item>Figma Tokens plugin — export token JSON for Style Dictionary pipeline</item>
        <item>Style Dictionary — build token transforms across platforms (CSS, iOS, Android)</item>
        <item>Storybook — component documentation host; agent generates .stories.tsx and .mdx</item>
        <item>Chromatic — visual regression testing for AI-generated component variants</item>
        <item>Supernova — design token management with multi-platform export; REST API</item>
        <item>Specify — design asset + token sync between Figma and code; REST API</item>
        <item>token-transformer — convert Figma Tokens plugin output to Style Dictionary format</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Documentation Pipeline">
      <list>
        <item>1. Haiku subagent reads component source (Storybook stories, TypeScript props, Figma export JSON)</item>
        <item>2. Generates documentation: component purpose, props table, usage examples, accessibility notes, do/don't</item>
        <item>3. Component engineer reviews for accuracy — verifies props, interaction states, ARIA behavior</item>
        <item>4. Design system lead approves before merging to published system</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Documentation generation works best on components with TypeScript prop types — poorly typed components produce poor documentation regardless of AI quality.</statement>
        <rationale>AI documentation quality is directly coupled to the quality of the code it reads. TypeScript types are the contract the agent uses to produce the props table.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Token Audit Workflow">
      <list>
        <item>1. Audit script scans codebase for hardcoded hex colors and px values</item>
        <item>2. Sonnet subagent produces replacement report with suggested token names and confidence ratings</item>
        <item>3. Low-confidence items flagged for human review</item>
        <item>4. Design system lead approves token replacement list before developers apply changes</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Feed the agent the token JSON and naming convention document as context before requesting any token suggestions — without it, AI invents names that violate the system's conventions.</statement>
        <rationale>Without the token registry as context, the agent cannot know whether a token already exists or what the naming pattern is. It will generate new token names that duplicate existing ones or violate conventions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Variant Generation Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run Chromatic visual regression testing on every AI-generated variant before merging — AI-generated code often has subtle visual differences from the design spec.</statement>
        <rationale>AI-generated variants look correct in code review but may have pixel-level rendering differences. Chromatic catches these before they reach production.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require agents to generate disabled, focus, and error states independently — a prompt saying "generate variants" produces only visual variants, missing interaction states.</statement>
        <rationale>Interaction states are not variants in the visual sense; they require different ARIA attributes, keyboard handling, and visual treatment. Agents omit them unless explicitly required.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Anti-Patterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>AI confuses semantic tokens (--color-action-primary) with primitive tokens (--color-blue-500) in suggestions.</description>
        <reason>Without explicit semantic/primitive distinction in the prompt, agents use the terms interchangeably. Semantic tokens must reference primitive tokens — not the reverse. Require explicit token layer distinction in every token-related prompt.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>AI-generated Storybook stories use deprecated CSF 2 syntax instead of CSF 3.</description>
        <reason>Without specifying the Storybook version in the prompt, agents default to CSF 2 patterns that generate deprecation warnings or fail in Storybook 8+. Always specify the exact Storybook and CSF version.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>AI-generated documentation not reviewed by the engineer who built the component.</description>
        <reason>AI documentation reads accurately but frequently contains subtle errors about edge cases, deprecated props, or platform-specific behavior. Only the component author can verify these details.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running token inconsistency detection on a codebase with more than 500 files in a single prompt.</description>
        <reason>Large codebases exceed single-prompt context. Chunk by directory; aggregate and de-duplicate results after all chunks are processed.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Creating new token names in AI-generated documentation without human approval.</description>
        <reason>AI invents token names that may duplicate existing tokens or violate naming conventions. Require the agent to reference existing token names only; flag any proposed new token for human review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using AI to build foundational design system structure from scratch.</description>
        <reason>AI amplifies existing structure; it does not create coherent foundations. A system built from AI output will have inconsistent token relationships, arbitrary naming, and no coherent design rationale. Human-led foundation design must come first.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <p>A Claude subagent (Haiku) reads the existing component library source (Storybook stories, CSS/Tailwind classes, Figma export JSON) and generates Markdown documentation stubs for each component including props table, usage examples, accessibility notes, and do/don't guidance. A Sonnet subagent performs token audit across the codebase, finds hardcoded values (hex colors, px values) that should be token references, and produces a replacement report. Human design system leads review both outputs before merging to the system.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Recommended Subagents">
      <list>
        <item>General Claude subagent (Haiku) — component documentation generation, token stub population</item>
        <item>General Claude subagent (Sonnet) — inconsistency detection, variant generation review, token suggestion critique</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Prompt Patterns">
      <p>Component documentation generation prompt:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are a design system engineer. Given this component definition:
[component code + existing props + Storybook story]

Generate documentation with these sections:
1. Component purpose (1 sentence)
2. Props table (name | type | default | description)
3. Usage examples (3 code snippets: basic, with variants, with accessibility props)
4. Accessibility notes (keyboard, ARIA roles, screen reader behavior)
5. Do / Don't (2 examples each)
6. Token references (list which design tokens this component uses)
Do not invent props that are not in the component code.]]></code>
      <p>Token audit prompt:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are auditing a codebase for design token compliance.
Given these files: [file list with content]
Find all hardcoded values that should be token references:
- Hex colors not using CSS custom properties
- Hardcoded px/rem spacing values not using spacing tokens
- Hardcoded font sizes not using typography tokens
For each finding: { file, line, hardcoded_value, suggested_token, confidence: High/Med/Low }
Flag Low confidence items for human review.]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools">
      <list>
        <item>style-dictionary — Build token transforms across platforms (CSS vars, iOS, Android); npm install style-dictionary / amzn.github.io/style-dictionary</item>
        <item>storybook — Component documentation host; agent can generate stories; npx storybook init / storybook.js.org</item>
        <item>token-transformer — Transform Figma Tokens plugin output to Style Dictionary format; npm install token-transformer</item>
        <item>chromatic — Visual regression testing for design system components; npm install chromatic / chromatic.com</item>
        <item>eslint-plugin-import — Detect direct color/spacing imports bypassing token layer; npm install eslint-plugin-import</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Services &amp; Apps">
      <list>
        <item>Figma — SaaS, agent-friendly (REST API); read token/component data; agent can extract design specs programmatically</item>
        <item>Figma Tokens plugin — SaaS plugin, agent-friendly (JSON export); export token JSON for Style Dictionary pipeline</item>
        <item>Storybook — OSS, agent-friendly (MDX/JSON); agent generates .stories.tsx and .mdx docs files</item>
        <item>Chromatic — SaaS, agent-friendly (CLI + API); visual diff detection for component changes</item>
        <item>Supernova — SaaS, agent-friendly (REST API); design token management with multi-platform export</item>
        <item>Specify — SaaS, agent-friendly (REST API); design asset + token sync between Figma and code</item>
        <item>Zeroheight — SaaS, partial agent-friendly (embed); documentation host; agent can generate content, not publish directly</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Token Audit Script Example">
      <p>Token audit script (finds hardcoded hex colors in CSS/SCSS):</p>
      <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[#!/usr/bin/env bash
# audit-hardcoded-tokens.sh
# Finds hardcoded hex colors and common px values not using CSS custom properties
set -euo pipefail

echo "=== Hardcoded Hex Colors ==="
grep -rn --include="*.css" --include="*.scss" --include="*.tsx" \
  -E '#[0-9a-fA-F]{3,8}(?![0-9a-fA-F])' \
  --exclude-dir=node_modules \
  . | grep -v 'var(--' | head -50

echo ""
echo "=== Hardcoded Spacing (px not in token pattern) ==="
grep -rn --include="*.css" --include="*.scss" \
  -E '[^-](\d{1,3}px)' \
  --exclude-dir=node_modules \
  . | grep -v 'var(--\|1px\|2px' | head -50]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Feed AI the token JSON and naming convention document as context before asking for any token suggestions — without it, AI invents names that violate the system's conventions</item>
        <item>Require the agent to reference existing token names when generating documentation — never allow it to create new token names without human approval</item>
        <item>Use AI for documentation first pass, not final text — component documentation must be verified by the engineer who built the component</item>
        <item>Set up Style Dictionary as the single source of truth before enabling AI variant generation — without it, AI variants will drift from the actual token values</item>
        <item>Run Chromatic visual regression testing on every AI-generated variant before merging — AI-generated code often has subtle visual differences from the design spec</item>
        <item>Documentation generation works best on components with good prop types (TypeScript) — poorly typed components produce poor documentation regardless of AI quality</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>AI-generated Storybook stories often use deprecated Storybook API (CSF 2 vs CSF 3) — specify the exact version in the prompt</item>
        <item>Token suggestion agents frequently confuse semantic tokens (--color-action-primary) with primitive tokens (--color-blue-500) — require explicit semantic/primitive distinction in the prompt</item>
        <item>Component variant generation requires the agent to understand disabled state, focus state, and error state independently — a prompt that only says "generate variants" produces only visual variants, missing interaction states</item>
        <item>Inconsistency detection on large codebases (&gt;500 files) exceeds single-prompt context — chunk by directory and aggregate results</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: design system lead must review all AI-generated documentation and token suggestions before merging to the published system — inaccurate system docs cause widespread misuse</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Where It Fails / Limitations">
      <list>
        <item>AI-generated component variants inherit semantic errors from the seed component — bad foundations produce bad variants at scale</item>
        <item>Token suggestion quality degrades without color theory constraints in the prompt — AI will produce accessible ratios if asked, but defaults to aesthetically arbitrary values</item>
        <item>Inconsistency detection requires the agent to have access to the full codebase; partial context produces incomplete results</item>
        <item>Documentation generation for stateful components (focus, hover, disabled, error) requires the agent to understand interaction semantics, not just visual appearance</item>
        <item>AI does not understand the human/team adoption problem — a technically correct component that breaks existing usage patterns will be ignored</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/audit-hardcoded-tokens.sh" purpose="Bash script to find hardcoded hex colors and px spacing"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-document-component.txt" purpose="Haiku prompt for component documentation generation"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-audit-tokens.txt" purpose="Sonnet prompt for token inconsistency detection"/>
    </templates>
